CLASSES AND OBJECTS
ACCESS MODIFIERS
GETTERS & SETTERS
Get: to return the value
Set: to modify the value

THIS: this keyword is used to refer to the current object.

ENCAPSULATION: is defined as the wrapping up of data & methods under a single unit. It also implements data hiding.
- aka data hiding -> private/default/protected -> useless/sensitive data

CONSTRUCTOR: is a special method which is invoked automatically at the time of object creation.
- constructors have the same name as class or structure.
- constructors dont have a return type.(not even void).
- constructors are only called once, at object creation.
- memory allocation happens when constructor is called.

TYPES of constructors:
- non-parameterised
- parameterised
- copy constructor: by default in cpp but created manually in java

CONSTRUCTOR OVERLOADING: too many constructors with different arguments and different data types. example of polymorphism.

SHALLOW & DEEP COPY
shallow: changes reflect
deep: changes don't reflect
GOOGLE LAZY COPY

DESTRUCTORS: special function in cpp that remove memory from object.
in java, garbage collector does that automatically by scanning and removing unused.

INHERITANCE: is when properties and methods of base class are passed on to a derived class.
TYPES:
- single level inheritance. base class -> derived class
- multi level inheritance. base class -> derived class -> derived class
- Hierarchical inheritance. base class -> derived class 1; base class -> derived class 2.
- hybrid inheritance
- multiple inheritance = only in cpp not in java

POLYMORPHISM
- compile time polymorphism = method overloading.
- run time polymorphism = method overriding.

METHOD OVERLOADING: multiple functions with the same name but different parameters
METHOD OVERRIDING: parent and child classes both contain the same function with a different definition.

PACKAGES in java: is a group of similar types of classes, interfaces and sub-packages.
- inbuilt packages
